"v.追赶，追求，追踪 无 v. (为了赶上或捕获而努力)跟随; 追求 【记】有了purpose才会有pursue 无 pursue (v.)  late 13c., ""to follow with hostile intent,"" from Anglo-French pursuer and directly from Old French poursuir (Modern  French poursuivre), variant of porsivre ""to chase, pursue, follow; continue, carry on,"" from Vulgar Latin *prosequare, from Latin prosequi ""follow, accompany, attend; follow after, escort; follow up, pursue,"" from pro- ""forward"" (see pro-) + sequi ""follow"" (see sequel). Meaning ""to proceed, to follow"" (a path, etc.), usually figurative (a course of action, etc.), is from late 14c. This sense also was in Latin. Related: Pursued; pursuing. For sense, compare prosecute."
